Diagnosis.
Recognized by the following set of features: antennal segment II in both sexes thinner than segment I (
Figs 52, 53
); pronotum with yellow, longitudinal stripe medially (
Figs 52, 53
); scutellum with three patches: two basolaterally and one apically (
Figs 52, 53
); corium with four yellow patches (
Figs 52, 53
); sclerite es1 short with basal two thirds nearly cylindrical, apical one third round, strongly serrate; es2 short, with basal two thirds strongly broadened toward apex, apical one third globose, strongly serrate; es3 nearly triangular, serrate; es4 weakly arcuate, sharply pointed apically and basally (
Fig. 135
); sensory lobe of left paramere weakly developed (
Figs 136, 137
).

Biology.
Often observed on fungi on the dead logs (
UHLER 1891
), probably associated with and feeding on pyrenomycete fungi (Euascomycetes: 
Xylariaceae
) (
WHEELER & WHEELER 1994
).
